oblem of academic insularity—where it comes from and where, if left to grow unchecked, it will go—and argues for the emergence of a more publicly and politically engaged scholar. This book is a call to make that path toward public engagement more acceptable and legitimate for those who do it; to enlarge the tent to be inclusive of multiple ways that one enacts the role of academic scholar in today's world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCollege teachersxPolitical activity. 0aCommunication in learning and scholarship. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspects. 0aLearning and scholarshipxPolitical aspects. 0aResearchxPolitical aspects. 0aScholarsxPolitical activity. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aPublic engagement.  aacademic research.  acrisis of relevance.  ameaning.  apurpose.  aresearch impact.  ascholarly career.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362925740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503629257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503629257/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles